Enjoy — this visualizer demonstrates why Bubble Sort, while easy to understand and sometimes efficient on nearly-sorted arrays, is generally much slower (O(n^2)) than Quick Sort and Merge Sort (O(n log n)) for average large inputs. If you want additional algorithms (Heap Sort, TimSort), integrated pseudocode, or CSV export of step counts, tell me which and I’ll extend the file.

Here's a single self-contained HTML file you can save (e.g., sort-compare.html) and open in a browser. It animates three sorts side-by-side on the same initial random array: bubble sort, insertion sort, and quicksort (Lomuto partition). Each panel shows a bar chart, highlights comparisons and swaps, counts steps (comparisons + swaps), and displays a short explanation of time complexities.

You can adjust array size and speed using the controls at the top. The code is self-contained — no external libraries.

