How this demonstrates the claim is wrong:
- Bubble Sort shows O(n^2) behavior: many compare/swap steps for larger arrays, visible in the "Steps" counter and slow animation.
- Quick Sort and Merge Sort perform far fewer steps (O(n log n) on average), finishing much faster for the same input.
- Merge Sort guarantees O(n log n); Quick Sort is usually fast in practice. Bubble Sort is generally only useful for educational/didactic purposes or tiny arrays.

